<span class="displaytext">today, sen. (candidate last)'s campaign held a conference call to defend his record of voting present on choice issues. but the (candidate last) campaign failed to address the fact that sen. (candidate last) voted present 129 times on a wide array of issues, including choice, privacy for victims of sexual assault, and school violence. in fact, the (candidate last) campaign claimed that sen. (candidate last)'s present votes were part of a legislative strategy but failed to mention that sen. (candidate last) was the lone present vote on a number of key issues. <p>sen. (candidate last)'s present votes by the numbers </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) voted 'present' 129 times while in the state senate.</b> [new york times, 12/20/07] </p><p><b>in 1999, sen. (candidate last) voted 'present' more often than he voted 'no':</b> according to state records, (candidate last) voted 'present' 43 times in 1999, while voting 'no' just 29 times. [ilga.gov] </p><p><b>at least 36 times, sen. (candidate last) was either the only state senator to vote present or was part of a group of six or fewer to vote that way.</b> [new york times, 12/20/07] </p><p>other present votes of interest: </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) was the only state senator to vote 'present' on a bill that sought to protect the privacy of sex-abuse victims, and the only state senator to not support the bill. </b>[hb854, passed 58-0-1, 05/11/99] </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) was the only state senator to vote 'present' on an adoption bill that imposed stricter requirements for parental fitness, and the only state senator to not support the bill.</b> [hb1298, passed 57-0-1, 5/6/1999] </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) voted 'present' on a bill that would increase penalties for the use of a firearm within 1,000 feet of a school.</b> the bill called for the mandatory adult persecution of a minor at least 15 years of age being tried for using a firearm within 1,000 feet of a school. [sb759, passed 52-1-5, 3/25/1999] </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) voted 'present' on a bill to prohibit the presence of adult sex shops near schools, places of worship, and day care facilities; bill allows local governments to regulate the presence of adult sex shops. </b> [sb609, passed 33-15-5, 3/29/2001] </p><p>illinois now on (candidate last)'s present votes on choice: </p><p>during sen. (candidate last)'s 2004 senate campaign, the illinois now pac did not recommend the endorsement of (candidate last) for u.s. senate because he refused to stand up for a woman's right to choose and repeatedly voted 'present' on important legislation. </p><p>as a state senator, (candidate full) voted 'present' on seven abortion bills, including a ban on 'partial birth abortion,' two parental notification laws and three 'born alive' bills. in each case, the right vote was clear, but sen. (candidate last) chose political cover over standing and fighting for his convictions. </p><p>"when we needed someone to take a stand, sen. (candidate last) took a pass," said grabenhofer. "he wasn't there for us then and we don't expect him to be now."</p></span>



